WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:02.200
And welcome to the session on rare

2
00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:05.520
cancer drug development.

3
00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:10.720
My name is Diane Pulte. I'm a clinical reviewer with the FDA

4
00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:15.120
in the Division of Hematologic Malignancies 1, which

5
00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:15.900
covers leukemia.

6
00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:19.439
These are my disclosures. I have no disclosures.

7
00:00:20.540 --> 00:00:23.680
The perspectives shared are those of the FDA staff and the panelists

8
00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:27.600
participating, not necessarily those of their respective organizations,

9
00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:29.080
and investigational drugs

10
00:00:30.020 --> 00:00:30.800
will be discussed.

11
00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:34.020
So just give a quick outline of the session.

12
00:00:35.260 --> 00:00:38.300
After the introduction, we'll have talks on challenges and opportunities in

13
00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:42.350
development of medications for rare diseases.

14
00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:46.800
Martha Donahue will present the FDA perspective, and then Eric Padron will

15
00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:48.100
present a perspective on

16
00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:53.300
development in CMML, and then Rachel Groseman will tell us about

17
00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:54.920
a successful development program.

18
00:00:55.600 --> 00:00:57.940
We'll have the panel discussion with Lisa Ranka,

19
00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:02.860
Josh Bilenker, and Nicole Andrews, and then we'll follow up with questions.

20
00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:05.459
Okay. Without further ado, Martha.

21
00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:10.460
Trip over something.

22
00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:17.120
Good afternoon, everybody. My name is Martha Donahue.

23
00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:20.580
I'm a pediatric oncologist by training, and I've worked at the FDA for

24
00:01:20.620 --> 00:01:24.280
about 15-plus years now. I currently serve as the associate

25
00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:28.290
director for Pediatric Oncology and Rare Cancers in the Oncology Center

26
00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:31.039
of Excellence. And it's such a pleasure to be here.

27
00:01:31.100 --> 00:01:32.940
Thank you all for joining.

28
00:01:35.510 --> 00:01:38.840
That's me, and I'm going to give a little bit of a 15-minute or so talk

29
00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:42.650
on the regulatory perspective on rare cancer drug development.

30
00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:46.040
We've already done that.

31
00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:48.860
Here's an outline of what I plan to cover.

32
00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:52.740
First, I'll provide an overview of the role of FDA's Oncology Center of

33
00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.620
Excellence, or OCE, and briefly describe some of the existing

34
00:01:56.680 --> 00:01:59.010
challenges to rare cancer drug development.

35
00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:02.960
Next, we'll discuss some of FDA's regulatory incentives and

36
00:02:03.020 --> 00:02:06.820
expedited programs to help encourage and support rare cancer

37
00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:10.220
drug development. And then I'll describe the evidentiary

38
00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:14.180
standards for FDA approval of drugs and biological products, and

39
00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:17.800
discuss potential regulatory flexibilities that we can apply to

40
00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:21.020
help hasten and make drug development for rare cancers more

41
00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:24.760
feasible, as well as some trial design and conduct

42
00:02:24.769 --> 00:02:28.680
considerations. And before wrapping up with some

43
00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:32.360
key takeaways, I'll point out a few FDA resources to support rare

44
00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:33.679
cancer drug development.

45
00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:40.810
This slide provides a high-level overview of FDA's Oncology Center of

46
00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:44.710
Excellence, or OCE. And OCE unites experts

47
00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:48.020
across the FDA to foster development of medical products for

48
00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:51.860
cancers. These experts work in three different centers in the

49
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.800
FDA: the Center for Drug Evaluation and Research, or CDER,

50
00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:56.100
which

51
00:02:56.920 --> 00:03:00.060
provides regulatory oversight of development for small molecules and

52
00:03:00.140 --> 00:03:03.750
antibody-based cancer therapies; the Center for Biologics

53
00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:07.340
Evaluation and Research, or CBER, which regulates the more

54
00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:10.590
complex biological products, including cell and gene therapies,

55
00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:15.530
as well as therapeutic vaccines; and the Center for Devices and

56
00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:19.490
Radiologic Health, or CDRH, which regulates the therapeutic devices,

57
00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:23.300
diagnostic devices, and in particular, when we think about for

58
00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:27.200
targeted therapies in oncology, the companion diagnostic tests,

59
00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:29.660
which are often used to select patients for targeted

60
00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:31.359
therapies.

61
00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:38.130
As depicted on this slide, and I think all of us know all too well,

62
00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:41.290
there are many challenges to successful drug development

63
00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:45.760
for rare cancers, which can make drug development in this space a risky

64
00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:48.000
proposition for pharmaceutical companies.

65
00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:52.120
And just a few include small patient numbers and geographic

66
00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:54.800
dispersion, which can make patient accrual more difficult.

67
00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:58.400
The natural history of rare cancers are often not well described.

68
00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:01.940
We're still learning every day little new things about all

69
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.720
cancers and rare cancers as well. We often have an

70
00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:08.890
insufficient understanding of cancer pathophysiology and molecular

71
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.300
characteristics of these cancers, limited or lack of

72
00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.780
timely access to molecular testing for many patients.

73
00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:19.940
There's also genotypic and phenotypic heterogeneity that's also

74
00:04:19.981 --> 00:04:23.420
characteristic of all cancers, but for rare cancers, those have even

75
00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:26.960
more difficult implications in terms of feasibility.

76
00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.730
There, of course, all of this rarity brings into play trial design complexities,

77
00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:35.840
including lack of viable therapies, sometimes for control treatment

78
00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:39.030
arms, reluctance to randomize in some settings as

79
00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:42.590
well, for lots of reasons. All of this can

80
00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:47.030
sometimes depress commercial interest in developing

81
00:04:47.180 --> 00:04:51.130
new drugs for rare cancers. And there are others that I'm sure you can all think

82
00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:54.860
of as well. The good news that I think is if we all work together, we can start

83
00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:56.920
tackling these issues. We've been doing this for a while.

84
00:04:56.940 --> 00:05:00.140
We're going to continue to do so, and I'm looking forward to hearing some ideas

85
00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:02.520
from all of you and the panelists in the next couple of minutes.

86
00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:09.010
There are regulatory incentives in place to help tip the balance in favor of

87
00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:12.730
drug development for rare cancers, and some of these are on this

88
00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:16.700
slide, and these include orphan drug designation, which uses the definition

89
00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:20.540
of rare disease defined by the Orphan Drug Act of a prevalence of less

90
00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.240
than 200,000 patients in the United States.

91
00:05:23.650 --> 00:05:27.200
To me, 200,000 seems like an awfully large number because, as we know, many rare

92
00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:31.300
cancers and subsets of common cancers based

93
00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:35.240
on molecular characteristics fall far behind those numbers, and with

94
00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:39.440
increasing rarity, of course, the challenges can sometimes enlarge as

95
00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:39.740
well.

96
00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:44.480
However, that being said, orphan drug designation does provide economic

97
00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:48.300
incentives for the development of orphan products by providing tax

98
00:05:48.360 --> 00:05:52.120
credits for qualified clinical trials, exemption from prescription

99
00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:55.920
drug user fees for FDA review, and seven years of marketing

100
00:05:55.940 --> 00:05:57.570
exclusivity following approval.

101
00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:02.240
The Office of Orphan Products Development at the FDA also offers 5

102
00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:05.580
to 12 new clinical trial grants for orphan products

103
00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:09.580
annually through a competitive process, and they've provided grants for several

104
00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.340
clinical trials for adult and pediatric rare

105
00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:15.976
cancers.The Rare Disease Priority Review Voucher

106
00:06:16.076 --> 00:06:19.506
Program, I'm happy to say, was recently reauthorized, and it

107
00:06:19.516 --> 00:06:23.456
confers transferable priority review vouchers following the original approval of a

108
00:06:23.736 --> 00:06:26.116
drug to treat a rare pediatric disease.

109
00:06:26.876 --> 00:06:30.516
I've heard anecdotally from stakeholders that this program provides meaningful

110
00:06:30.576 --> 00:06:34.516
incentives to companies, particularly small pharma, for the development

111
00:06:34.536 --> 00:06:36.796
of drugs to treat pediatric cancers.

112
00:06:36.816 --> 00:06:40.286
And several vouchers have been awarded following approval of

113
00:06:40.316 --> 00:06:44.296
products to treat pediatric cancers, including the recent award

114
00:06:44.316 --> 00:06:47.626
of a pediatric voucher for dardavirpan following

115
00:06:48.196 --> 00:06:51.576
the 2025 approval of the drug for the treatment of

116
00:06:51.716 --> 00:06:54.776
H3K27M mutant diffuse midline glioma.

117
00:06:56.116 --> 00:07:00.076
The Best Pharmaceutical for Children Act request process provides additional

118
00:07:00.136 --> 00:07:03.876
incentives for development of drugs for pediatric cancers by

119
00:07:03.936 --> 00:07:07.836
conferring six months additional exclusivity to the active moiety in

120
00:07:07.856 --> 00:07:11.596
return for submission of reports from voluntarily conducted pediatric

121
00:07:11.696 --> 00:07:13.816
studies outlined in the written request.

122
00:07:14.676 --> 00:07:18.516
As we know, despite these incentives, there's still a high unmet need for new drugs

123
00:07:18.556 --> 00:07:22.336
to treat patients with rare cancers, and in particular, those that do not

124
00:07:22.376 --> 00:07:24.576
share targets with more common cancers.

125
00:07:27.536 --> 00:07:30.796
FDA also has expedited programs, which are intended to

126
00:07:30.856 --> 00:07:34.736
facilitate and speed up development and review of drugs that address

127
00:07:34.896 --> 00:07:38.476
unmet medical needs in the treatment of serious and life-threatening

128
00:07:38.516 --> 00:07:42.396
conditions, such as rare cancers, and it is very typical

129
00:07:42.416 --> 00:07:46.376
for rare cancer drug development programs to take advantage of one or more of

130
00:07:46.436 --> 00:07:50.096
these programs. We encourage sponsors to consider

131
00:07:50.136 --> 00:07:53.936
applying for these programs early in development,

132
00:07:54.656 --> 00:07:58.446
as early as possible, and we'll discuss accelerated approval shortly

133
00:07:59.236 --> 00:08:03.086
in a bit more detail. But in the interest of time, I'll just note that

134
00:08:03.116 --> 00:08:06.856
Fast Track and Breakthrough Therapy designations provide opportunities for

135
00:08:06.876 --> 00:08:10.796
increased interaction with the agency, particularly experts in the

136
00:08:10.856 --> 00:08:14.376
agency who are pretty experienced throughout drug development,

137
00:08:14.796 --> 00:08:17.836
as well as rolling review in the case of Fast Track designation.

138
00:08:18.876 --> 00:08:22.536
And priority review shortens our application review time by four

139
00:08:22.596 --> 00:08:26.556
months, although I will note that often our reviews are much shorter than what

140
00:08:26.596 --> 00:08:27.316
is required.

141
00:08:31.636 --> 00:08:35.146
I'll move on to the requirements for FDA approval of drugs and

142
00:08:35.216 --> 00:08:35.886
biologics.

143
00:08:36.716 --> 00:08:40.606
The requirements for FDA approval are outlined in the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic

144
00:08:40.736 --> 00:08:44.316
Act. A drug's effectiveness must be established by what we term

145
00:08:44.396 --> 00:08:48.166
substantial evidence, which consists of adequate and well-controlled investigations

146
00:08:48.196 --> 00:08:50.416
that are performed by qualified experts.

147
00:08:50.886 --> 00:08:51.976
And the information from these

148
00:08:52.996 --> 00:08:56.936
investigations should provide data that is sufficient to form the basis

149
00:08:57.236 --> 00:09:00.996
for a fair and responsible conclusion by experts that the drug

150
00:09:01.156 --> 00:09:03.156
has the effect that it claims to have.

151
00:09:03.476 --> 00:09:07.276
In our case, that the drug or biologic is effective in treating cancer.

152
00:09:08.576 --> 00:09:12.436
One thing to note is that this standard applies to both common and rare

153
00:09:12.536 --> 00:09:15.376
cancers. The evidentiary requirements are the same

154
00:09:17.416 --> 00:09:19.176
for us in order to make an approval decision.

155
00:09:19.236 --> 00:09:22.916
It's not that there's a lesser bar for rare cancers compared to less rare

156
00:09:22.956 --> 00:09:26.916
cancers. Although not on this slide, we also have to conclude

157
00:09:26.926 --> 00:09:30.676
that the overall balance of safety and effectiveness is such that the

158
00:09:30.696 --> 00:09:32.716
benefits of the drug outweigh the risks.

159
00:09:34.816 --> 00:09:38.576
There are two approval pathways for drugs and biologics: accelerated

160
00:09:38.596 --> 00:09:41.446
approval and regular or traditional approval.

161
00:09:42.345 --> 00:09:46.306
Accelerated approval allows for earlier approval of drugs for serious and

162
00:09:46.336 --> 00:09:50.296
life-threatening conditions that address unmet medical needs, and the

163
00:09:50.316 --> 00:09:53.916
guiding principle for approval is the same for both approval

164
00:09:53.936 --> 00:09:57.875
pathways. But there are a few differences to highlight between the two.

165
00:09:59.336 --> 00:10:02.956
While there are no requirements for a product to be better than available

166
00:10:03.016 --> 00:10:06.976
therapies for regular approval, for a drug to receive accelerated

167
00:10:07.016 --> 00:10:10.956
approval, it must provide a meaningful therapeutic benefit over available

168
00:10:11.036 --> 00:10:14.796
therapies. Accelerated approval is also based on an intermediate

169
00:10:14.856 --> 00:10:18.676
clinical endpoint that is likely to predict clinical benefit, rather than a

170
00:10:18.696 --> 00:10:21.536
direct measure of clinical benefit, such as survival.

171
00:10:22.336 --> 00:10:25.856
Traditional approval is based on an endpoint that demonstrates direct clinical

172
00:10:25.896 --> 00:10:26.336
benefit,

173
00:10:27.596 --> 00:10:31.436
as I just said, such as overall survival or some improvement in patient-related

174
00:10:31.956 --> 00:10:35.576
symptoms would be another. In oncology, we often use

175
00:10:35.616 --> 00:10:39.516
intermediate clinical endpoints that directly measure the tumor itself, such

176
00:10:39.556 --> 00:10:42.996
as overall response rate or progression-free survival.

177
00:10:43.016 --> 00:10:46.676
And these endpoints can be used to support either accelerated or regular

178
00:10:46.716 --> 00:10:49.576
approval, depending upon the context.

179
00:10:49.616 --> 00:10:53.206
Oncology, by far, has the most accelerated approvals among medical

180
00:10:53.256 --> 00:10:56.896
specialties, accounting for about 80% of accelerated approvals by

181
00:10:56.976 --> 00:11:00.776
FDA in the last decade. And this reflects not only the urgent

182
00:11:00.876 --> 00:11:04.836
nature of cancer treatment and high unmet medical need, but also the

183
00:11:04.876 --> 00:11:08.656
field's advancement in identifying meaningful biomarkers and intermediate

184
00:11:08.696 --> 00:11:09.256
endpoints.

185
00:11:12.796 --> 00:11:15.716
Now that I've talked a little bit about the requirements for approval, I'd like to

186
00:11:15.776 --> 00:11:19.076
describe how our regulations mandate that FDA exert

187
00:11:19.116 --> 00:11:22.996
flexibility in our assessment of whether the regulatory standards for approval

188
00:11:23.006 --> 00:11:26.466
are met, taking into account unmet medical need, among other

189
00:11:26.496 --> 00:11:27.026
factors.

190
00:11:28.656 --> 00:11:32.196
As you can see, based on the first regulatory citation, we're required to

191
00:11:32.236 --> 00:11:35.736
exercise our judgment at the FDA to determine the type and

192
00:11:35.836 --> 00:11:39.116
quantity of information that the applicant should provide in their

193
00:11:39.196 --> 00:11:40.916
application to support approval.

194
00:11:41.556 --> 00:11:45.276
Not only that, but under the Code of Federal Regulations, for drugs

195
00:11:45.316 --> 00:11:48.376
intended to treat life-threatening and severely debilitating

196
00:11:48.456 --> 00:11:51.996
diseases, such as rare cancers, we acknowledge that it is

197
00:11:52.056 --> 00:11:55.496
appropriate to exercise broad flexibility in applying the

198
00:11:55.516 --> 00:11:59.376
statutory standards while preserving appropriate guarantees of

199
00:11:59.476 --> 00:12:00.776
safety and effectiveness.

200
00:12:02.976 --> 00:12:04.216
There are several ways that we

201
00:12:05.056 --> 00:12:07.236
at the FDA can potentially support

202
00:12:08.116 --> 00:12:11.096
more flexibility, as listed on this slide.

203
00:12:11.136 --> 00:12:15.016
We have exerted flexibility in terms of the

204
00:12:15.036 --> 00:12:18.776
number of trials required, the design of these trials, trial

205
00:12:18.816 --> 00:12:22.586
endpoints, as well as statistical considerations of trials supporting

206
00:12:22.596 --> 00:12:23.396
approval when

207
00:12:23.436 --> 00:12:27.204
appropriate.Under certain

208
00:12:27.284 --> 00:12:31.234
circumstances, FDA can conclude that one adequate and well-controlled

209
00:12:31.324 --> 00:12:35.044
clinical investigation, plus confirmatory evidence, is sufficient to

210
00:12:35.084 --> 00:12:39.014
establish effectiveness. And confirmatory evidence can take a number of

211
00:12:39.064 --> 00:12:42.704
forms, including things such as mechanistic or pharmacodynamic

212
00:12:42.764 --> 00:12:43.244
evidence,

213
00:12:44.244 --> 00:12:48.134
clinical evidence from related indications, evidence from relevant animal

214
00:12:48.224 --> 00:12:51.984
models, and so on. In a recent "New

215
00:12:52.024 --> 00:12:55.664
England Journal of Medicine" article, Doctors Prasad and Makary

216
00:12:56.184 --> 00:12:59.684
described one pivotal trial as the new default

217
00:12:59.784 --> 00:13:01.464
option for FDA approval,

218
00:13:02.484 --> 00:13:06.164
and also noted that in some fields, such as oncology, single

219
00:13:06.264 --> 00:13:08.524
trials have supported the majority of drug approvals.

220
00:13:09.124 --> 00:13:12.693
In other words, approval decisions based on the result of one adequate and

221
00:13:12.724 --> 00:13:16.693
well-controlled trial are the rule rather than the exception

222
00:13:16.724 --> 00:13:17.464
in oncology.

223
00:13:19.624 --> 00:13:22.724
Additionally, data from single-arm trials have often been used in oncology to

224
00:13:22.744 --> 00:13:24.784
support approval of drugs as single agents.

225
00:13:25.204 --> 00:13:28.824
Particularly in the refractory setting, we have approved single-agent

226
00:13:28.864 --> 00:13:32.244
treatments for both common and rare cancers based upon trials with primary

227
00:13:32.284 --> 00:13:36.024
endpoints of overall response rate, as well as durability of response.

228
00:13:36.044 --> 00:13:40.024
And these response rate endpoints can be interpreted in single-arm trials

229
00:13:40.064 --> 00:13:43.354
because cancers don't typically regress on their own without effective

230
00:13:43.464 --> 00:13:47.324
treatment. However, there are real limitations to single-arm designs that we

231
00:13:47.344 --> 00:13:51.094
should keep in mind that can lead to uncertainty in the assessment of safety and

232
00:13:51.124 --> 00:13:55.094
effectiveness. In other words, even for the drug development in rare cancers,

233
00:13:55.444 --> 00:13:57.844
single-arm designs are not always the ideal approach.

234
00:13:58.824 --> 00:14:02.264
With single-arm designs in rare cancer safety databases, as we know, are often

235
00:14:02.364 --> 00:14:06.164
small, and assessment of whether the drug causes the adverse events seen in the

236
00:14:06.184 --> 00:14:09.004
trial can be difficult with non-randomized designs.

237
00:14:09.644 --> 00:14:13.344
Additionally, important time to event endpoints such as survival and time to tumor

238
00:14:13.404 --> 00:14:16.904
progression are generally not interpretable due to confounding factors.

239
00:14:17.874 --> 00:14:21.724
And another important limitation is that the clinical implications of drugs that

240
00:14:21.804 --> 00:14:25.404
have low overall response rates are not easily understood, and it can be

241
00:14:25.464 --> 00:14:29.124
difficult to determine whether the observed responses are predictive of whether a

242
00:14:29.164 --> 00:14:31.904
patient's benefiting from treatment or not.

243
00:14:31.944 --> 00:14:35.133
For these reasons, we do recommend careful consideration of whether randomized

244
00:14:35.144 --> 00:14:38.874
designs are the most appropriate design in rare cancers and,

245
00:14:39.164 --> 00:14:40.584
of course, more common cancers.

246
00:14:43.264 --> 00:14:47.224
There are many approaches to trial design conduct and statistical analysis

247
00:14:47.244 --> 00:14:50.364
that can be leveraged to help facilitate development of new therapies for rare

248
00:14:50.404 --> 00:14:52.144
cancers, and I put a few on this slide.

249
00:14:52.484 --> 00:14:56.364
This includes seamless designs, use of expansion cohorts, platform trials,

250
00:14:56.704 --> 00:15:00.154
incorporation of adaptive design elements into clinical trials,

251
00:15:00.944 --> 00:15:04.544
Bayesian statistics, as well as model-informed approaches,

252
00:15:04.584 --> 00:15:08.264
and careful use of clinical outcome assessment endpoints as well.

253
00:15:09.164 --> 00:15:12.844
We emphasize the importance of patient-informed drug development,

254
00:15:13.204 --> 00:15:16.904
consideration of multi-regional trials, and thinking about

255
00:15:17.164 --> 00:15:21.124
incorporation of pragmatic clinical trial design elements to make trials

256
00:15:21.184 --> 00:15:22.374
more patient-centric.

257
00:15:28.944 --> 00:15:32.884
I've provided a few relevant resources on this slide for you

258
00:15:32.924 --> 00:15:36.844
to review at your leisure, including FDA guidances and a few of the many

259
00:15:36.904 --> 00:15:40.404
OCE programs and initiatives that can be leveraged to support cancer drug

260
00:15:40.464 --> 00:15:44.444
development. More information on these guidances and OCE programs can be

261
00:15:44.484 --> 00:15:45.204
found online.

262
00:15:47.684 --> 00:15:51.234
I'd like to briefly call your attention to funding opportunities for extramural

263
00:15:51.284 --> 00:15:54.624
research, including broad agency announcements, notice of funding

264
00:15:54.684 --> 00:15:58.504
opportunities, and the previously mentioned orphan products grants.

265
00:15:58.544 --> 00:16:02.524
And please visit the OCE Scientific Collaborative website for additional

266
00:16:02.544 --> 00:16:03.844
information if you're interested.

267
00:16:05.784 --> 00:16:09.114
I'd also like to call out my friends and colleagues at Project Facilitate, which is

268
00:16:09.144 --> 00:16:13.044
an OCE program. It's basically a call center to help guide physicians who are

269
00:16:13.084 --> 00:16:17.064
seeking single patient INDs for expanded access use of investigational

270
00:16:17.104 --> 00:16:20.904
products for their patients. This is a really useful team that can

271
00:16:20.924 --> 00:16:24.404
help guide you through the process if you're uncertain how to do it, or even if you

272
00:16:24.484 --> 00:16:28.444
have experience. And they're very approachable, so please do

273
00:16:28.504 --> 00:16:32.384
take advantage of the resources there if you have that

274
00:16:32.444 --> 00:16:33.104
situation.

275
00:16:34.964 --> 00:16:38.824
And I'd like to leave you guys with just a few key takeaways to summarize my talk.

276
00:16:39.584 --> 00:16:43.344
Development of drugs to treat rare cancers can be challenging, but we at the FDA

277
00:16:43.354 --> 00:16:47.304
have numerous resources that can be leveraged to help overcome these obstacles, and

278
00:16:47.323 --> 00:16:50.964
we are really interested in working with you to help figure out the best

279
00:16:51.004 --> 00:16:54.704
development programs for drugs for the specific rare cancer you're

280
00:16:54.744 --> 00:16:55.444
interested in.

281
00:16:56.324 --> 00:17:00.284
FDA approval does require substantial evidence of effectiveness, irrespective of

282
00:17:00.344 --> 00:17:04.094
cancer prevalence. And randomized trials should always be considered,

283
00:17:05.144 --> 00:17:08.795
especially early in the drug development process for rare cancers,

284
00:17:09.444 --> 00:17:11.644
where every patient's data matters.

285
00:17:12.144 --> 00:17:14.154
Well, it matters no matter what, but you know what I'm saying.

286
00:17:14.664 --> 00:17:17.285
We have to be especially thoughtful about rare cancers.

287
00:17:17.785 --> 00:17:21.734
We can exercise broad flexibility in applying the statutory standards

288
00:17:21.785 --> 00:17:25.604
for safety and effectiveness when warranted, and we are eager to discuss

289
00:17:26.045 --> 00:17:29.804
these approaches with people interested in drug development for rare

290
00:17:29.884 --> 00:17:33.784
cancers, in particular, understanding that no one size fits all approach can

291
00:17:33.824 --> 00:17:37.264
be applied. We do recommend early and frequent interaction with

292
00:17:37.304 --> 00:17:41.264
stakeholders to discuss development for rare cancers, and we do

293
00:17:41.304 --> 00:17:45.024
invite and encourage industry sponsors to bring

294
00:17:45.104 --> 00:17:48.044
in representatives from every stakeholder group into these meetings,

295
00:17:48.384 --> 00:17:52.104
representatives from patient advocacy, the investigators, as well

296
00:17:52.184 --> 00:17:55.704
as the industry sponsor representatives, because that can really help promote

297
00:17:55.744 --> 00:17:58.684
clearer communication and more productive discussions.

298
00:18:00.364 --> 00:18:03.924
I'd like to thank the AACR staff for

299
00:18:03.964 --> 00:18:07.824
helping to support us in this meeting, as well as my colleagues at the

300
00:18:07.904 --> 00:18:10.444
FDA, and thank all of you for being here, of course.

301
00:18:10.524 --> 00:18:14.484
Please do reach out to me, or the OCE Rare Cancer Program if you have

302
00:18:14.524 --> 00:18:18.384
questions or needs. And I also wanted to let you know that we are interested in

303
00:18:18.424 --> 00:18:20.944
hiring talented people who want to join our team.

304
00:18:21.054 --> 00:18:24.584
So if you are interested or know somebody who might be, please feel free to reach

305
00:18:24.624 --> 00:18:28.284
out to us on this email, and thank you for your attention, and I will turn it

306
00:18:28.324 --> 00:18:29.604
back to my colleague, Diane.

307
00:18:35.828 --> 00:18:38.538
Thank you, Martha. Next, I have Eric Padron who will

308
00:18:39.588 --> 00:18:43.148
speak on barriers to clinical development of therapeutics for chronic

309
00:18:43.168 --> 00:18:44.748
myelomonocytic leukemia.

310
00:18:52.368 --> 00:18:55.728
Okay. Good afternoon, everybody. Can you guys hear me okay?

311
00:18:57.008 --> 00:18:59.768
Well, it's an honor to be here. I'd like to start by thanking

312
00:19:00.588 --> 00:19:04.108
Diane and Martha, and the FDA

313
00:19:04.168 --> 00:19:06.958
for the kind invitation. I'd like to thank

314
00:19:07.528 --> 00:19:11.058
AACR for sponsoring this important topic.

315
00:19:11.368 --> 00:19:15.318
And I'd like to start by saying, at least for me, one of the most compelling

316
00:19:15.328 --> 00:19:18.788
reasons why this is important. If you look at, for example,

317
00:19:19.288 --> 00:19:22.188
the National Cancer Institute definition of a rare cancer,

318
00:19:23.348 --> 00:19:27.008
30% of all patients with cancer have a rare cancer.

319
00:19:27.028 --> 00:19:30.408
And while there are many flavors of this,

320
00:19:31.008 --> 00:19:34.848
it becomes very clear that the barriers that we're going to talk about

321
00:19:34.908 --> 00:19:36.808
today matter for a lot of people.

322
00:19:38.128 --> 00:19:41.548
I'm going to tell you about one of these rare cancers, chronic myelomonocytic

323
00:19:41.568 --> 00:19:43.468
leukemia. I'll give you a little

324
00:19:45.528 --> 00:19:48.338
primer on the disease and its clinical development.

325
00:19:49.128 --> 00:19:53.088
And I'll warn you that this is a journey that's far from over, but I hope that

326
00:19:53.148 --> 00:19:57.068
some of the barriers that we've encountered help fuel the discussion.

327
00:19:57.428 --> 00:19:57.588
So,

328
00:19:59.428 --> 00:20:00.718
this is my disclosure slide.

329
00:20:02.968 --> 00:20:06.128
Okay, so what is CMML? So CMML is a

330
00:20:06.148 --> 00:20:09.938
disease, and the pathologic hallmark of CMML is a

331
00:20:09.988 --> 00:20:13.848
classical monocytosis. What I mean by that is, in humans, there are three

332
00:20:13.888 --> 00:20:17.348
types of monocytes: classical, intermediate, and non-classical.

333
00:20:17.498 --> 00:20:21.408
And in CMML, as compared to normal, you see a highly

334
00:20:21.428 --> 00:20:23.628
restricted classical monocytosis.

335
00:20:25.008 --> 00:20:28.948
Patients with CMML have a homogenous spectrum of

336
00:20:28.988 --> 00:20:32.978
mutations, but unfortunately, and I'll discuss that in

337
00:20:33.028 --> 00:20:33.508
a minute,

338
00:20:34.408 --> 00:20:37.248
those homogenous mutations are in disparate pathways.

339
00:20:37.288 --> 00:20:38.228
So we're talking about

340
00:20:39.388 --> 00:20:43.368
DNA methylation, histone modifications, RAS pathway signaling,

341
00:20:43.488 --> 00:20:46.988
splicing. So very few number of mutations, but

342
00:20:47.008 --> 00:20:48.368
disparate biology.

343
00:20:49.968 --> 00:20:53.328
We've shown a long time ago that maybe one of the convergent

344
00:20:53.408 --> 00:20:57.388
mechanisms is hypersensitivity to a cytokine called GM-CSF,

345
00:20:57.448 --> 00:21:01.258
and I'll tell you why I think that's important for the future of CMML drug

346
00:21:01.328 --> 00:21:01.788
development.

347
00:21:02.758 --> 00:21:06.538
These patients not only have a severe cancer that is

348
00:21:06.568 --> 00:21:10.148
life-threatening, but they have really dramatic

349
00:21:10.188 --> 00:21:13.948
impairments in quality of life. And this could be very

350
00:21:14.068 --> 00:21:17.808
similar to those that we know in other chronic myeloid neoplasms, like

351
00:21:17.818 --> 00:21:21.468
myelofibrosis, to include massive splenomegaly, weight loss, et cetera.

352
00:21:23.468 --> 00:21:25.648
Unlike myelofibrosis and some of the other

353
00:21:26.548 --> 00:21:30.448
chronic hematologic malignancies, CMML is an aggressive

354
00:21:30.548 --> 00:21:34.328
disease with a median survival of, unfortunately, 32 months.

355
00:21:35.748 --> 00:21:39.548
And unlike its related disease, myelodysplastic syndrome, there are

356
00:21:39.568 --> 00:21:39.808
no

357
00:21:40.828 --> 00:21:44.608
FDA-approved drugs that alter the natural history of the

358
00:21:44.688 --> 00:21:45.208
disease.

359
00:21:46.388 --> 00:21:50.328
Now, that's not to say that there aren't any FDA-approved drugs for CMML, and

360
00:21:50.368 --> 00:21:53.188
it's a little bit of a unique clinical development history.

361
00:21:53.288 --> 00:21:57.108
So this is the timeline. So I can make the font really big because

362
00:21:57.148 --> 00:21:58.488
there's not that many things that

363
00:21:59.628 --> 00:22:03.348
have been developed. But the moral of this story is that really

364
00:22:03.428 --> 00:22:05.028
azacitidine, decitabine,

365
00:22:05.868 --> 00:22:09.808
and oral decitabine in Covi were all approved really

366
00:22:10.668 --> 00:22:12.248
in a clinical trial

367
00:22:14.548 --> 00:22:18.468
that included MDS patients. In fact, if you look at the azacitidine

368
00:22:18.528 --> 00:22:22.048
trial, the pivotal trial in 2001, there were only

369
00:22:22.108 --> 00:22:24.888
11 patients with CMML in that study.

370
00:22:24.928 --> 00:22:28.808
And so there really hasn't been any CMML specific drugs approved to

371
00:22:28.848 --> 00:22:29.168
date.

372
00:22:30.988 --> 00:22:34.928
So as I thought about why, I organized it into

373
00:22:34.988 --> 00:22:36.827
four categories. I'm sure there's more.

374
00:22:37.788 --> 00:22:39.088
And I'll talk a little bit about that.

375
00:22:39.148 --> 00:22:43.028
So there's the economic case, there's the biology, which I hinted to,

376
00:22:44.128 --> 00:22:48.008
there's can you even do a Phase III study, and

377
00:22:48.048 --> 00:22:50.268
then what are the endpoints and what is the pathway?

378
00:22:51.588 --> 00:22:51.767
So

379
00:22:52.628 --> 00:22:56.128
let's talk a little bit about the economic case, and this is what I always talk to

380
00:22:56.168 --> 00:23:00.078
my industry collaborators about is, yes, CMML is

381
00:23:00.168 --> 00:23:04.008
rare, just like any hematologic malignancy in adults, but it's

382
00:23:04.028 --> 00:23:07.768
not that rare. And if you look at its incidence, it's comparable to

383
00:23:07.828 --> 00:23:11.648
other myeloproliferative neoplasms that have had successful drug

384
00:23:11.728 --> 00:23:15.448
approvals. The challenge is that the prevalence of these

385
00:23:15.488 --> 00:23:19.108
diseases is far fewer. But like we've learned in chronic myeloid

386
00:23:19.128 --> 00:23:22.938
leukemia and other diseases, if you have effective therapy, that

387
00:23:22.968 --> 00:23:25.408
therapy would augment the prevalence of the disease.

388
00:23:27.088 --> 00:23:30.948
So to build on that, I took a little bit of a deep dive and

389
00:23:31.028 --> 00:23:34.288
asked how many diseases that have similar

390
00:23:34.348 --> 00:23:37.408
incidence have FDA-approved drugs.

391
00:23:37.488 --> 00:23:41.328
I'm sure this list is not exhaustive, but here's a list of

392
00:23:41.368 --> 00:23:42.348
diseases that have

393
00:23:43.308 --> 00:23:45.148
comparable or smaller incidence.

394
00:23:45.608 --> 00:23:48.388
And these are the FDA-approved drugs that have been approved.

395
00:23:48.448 --> 00:23:52.268
I won't go over all of them, but I'll just highlight one, PNH,

396
00:23:52.388 --> 00:23:56.348
for example. There are six FDA-approved drugs, and it's a disease that

397
00:23:56.428 --> 00:24:00.088
is, at best, comparable, if not more

398
00:24:00.128 --> 00:24:02.148
rare than CMML. So why?

399
00:24:03.968 --> 00:24:07.588
So as you take a deeper dive into these diseases, what you

400
00:24:07.628 --> 00:24:09.658
find is there are one of two things.

401
00:24:10.328 --> 00:24:13.848
Either there is a clear somatic mutation that is

402
00:24:13.908 --> 00:24:16.708
targetable in the vast majority of cases.

403
00:24:16.968 --> 00:24:20.568
You can see that in PNH, you can see it in Hairy cell, you can see that in

404
00:24:20.608 --> 00:24:24.498
Waldenstrom's, you can see it in systemic mastocytosis, you could see that

405
00:24:24.528 --> 00:24:25.048
in GIST.

406
00:24:25.978 --> 00:24:29.488
And in those that don't have a targetable mutation

407
00:24:29.768 --> 00:24:33.428
in, say, over 80% of cases, there happens to be

408
00:24:33.508 --> 00:24:37.098
convergent biology. So JAK-STAT signaling in MPNs, for

409
00:24:37.148 --> 00:24:40.084
exampleMerkel cell polyomavirus,

410
00:24:40.644 --> 00:24:44.114
CD123 expression, and BPDCN. So these are all convergent

411
00:24:44.144 --> 00:24:47.974
mechanisms that make a rare cancer not that

412
00:24:47.984 --> 00:24:51.384
rare because it doesn't need to be sliced from a therapeutic standpoint

413
00:24:52.264 --> 00:24:52.984
in many ways.

414
00:24:55.024 --> 00:24:57.854
So what are we doing in CMML? And I broadly

415
00:24:58.544 --> 00:25:01.844
categorized the preclinical landscape of CMML into two

416
00:25:02.384 --> 00:25:05.404
categories. The first is the mutation-directed therapies.

417
00:25:05.464 --> 00:25:09.244
Of course, that makes it hard because it's a rare disease, and then this is a

418
00:25:09.344 --> 00:25:13.224
subset of a rare disease. But there are ways to move

419
00:25:13.264 --> 00:25:16.304
these therapies forward that we can talk about in the session.

420
00:25:16.364 --> 00:25:19.024
But what I'll just highlight is one study.

421
00:25:19.084 --> 00:25:22.984
This work was led by Julia Maxson at OHSU, and

422
00:25:23.984 --> 00:25:27.914
she focused on a mutation in a gene called SETBP1, and

423
00:25:27.944 --> 00:25:31.854
this gene's mutated in about 15% of cases with

424
00:25:31.884 --> 00:25:35.004
CMML and almost never in other

425
00:25:35.044 --> 00:25:39.004
diseases. And doing really exciting

426
00:25:39.024 --> 00:25:42.984
preclinical work, she found that mutated SETBP1

427
00:25:43.904 --> 00:25:45.184
interacts with

428
00:25:46.144 --> 00:25:49.664
missed acetyltransferases and that targeting KAT6 and 7

429
00:25:50.424 --> 00:25:54.364
could be a viable strategy. So this is just one example of where I think it all

430
00:25:54.464 --> 00:25:57.644
starts, which is the biology and identifying novel therapeutic

431
00:25:57.724 --> 00:25:58.484
vulnerabilities.

432
00:25:59.744 --> 00:26:02.604
But again, one of the things that is also important is to really try and find

433
00:26:02.644 --> 00:26:06.444
convergent biology, especially in rare cancers, because there's just not

434
00:26:06.484 --> 00:26:09.004
enough patients to slice the entire pie.

435
00:26:09.024 --> 00:26:12.744
And one of the things, as I mentioned earlier, could be the hyperactivity or the

436
00:26:13.304 --> 00:26:15.544
hyperactivity of GM-CSF signaling.

437
00:26:16.504 --> 00:26:19.944
And so what this is aimed to depict is that just like

438
00:26:20.024 --> 00:26:23.984
other myeloid diseases, CMML is a disease of the stem cell

439
00:26:24.024 --> 00:26:27.204
in which pre-leukemic somatic mutations occur, so-called clonal

440
00:26:27.214 --> 00:26:30.804
hematopoiesis. And then as the disease

441
00:26:30.814 --> 00:26:34.544
evolves, there becomes a expansion of

442
00:26:34.564 --> 00:26:37.724
cells that are very sensitive to GM-CSF.

443
00:26:38.224 --> 00:26:40.804
And the question is, can this be therapeutically targeted?

444
00:26:41.304 --> 00:26:42.624
And the short answer is we think so.

445
00:26:42.704 --> 00:26:45.764
So these are two clinical trials that have already been completed,

446
00:26:46.543 --> 00:26:50.484
single-arm studies, which show that perhaps either by its upstream

447
00:26:50.584 --> 00:26:54.344
kinase, JAK2, in the context of ruxolitinib, or at the level

448
00:26:54.584 --> 00:26:57.613
of a neutralizing antibody in

449
00:26:57.864 --> 00:27:01.304
lenzilumab, there is now proof of concept that targeting

450
00:27:01.344 --> 00:27:04.214
GM-CSF signaling could lead to a

451
00:27:04.244 --> 00:27:08.194
disease-modifying therapy in CMML, and

452
00:27:08.224 --> 00:27:11.584
not just in one genetic subset. So we're excited about this and

453
00:27:12.004 --> 00:27:14.244
hopefully these things will be developed further.

454
00:27:15.944 --> 00:27:16.424
And then

455
00:27:17.324 --> 00:27:21.094
can Phase III studies be done? That's a question that I'm always

456
00:27:21.184 --> 00:27:25.004
asked, and I always start by saying, because there's such an opportunity,

457
00:27:25.024 --> 00:27:28.654
because there are not many options for these patients, even though it's

458
00:27:28.664 --> 00:27:30.444
rare, the clinical trials that

459
00:27:33.524 --> 00:27:37.184
are designed for these diseases in fact accrue quite quickly.

460
00:27:38.124 --> 00:27:41.904
So this is a Phase III study that was completed by the

461
00:27:41.964 --> 00:27:44.504
GFM group led by Raphael Itzkenson.

462
00:27:44.584 --> 00:27:48.024
So these were all sites in Europe and Paris, and they

463
00:27:48.064 --> 00:27:51.364
randomized patients to either receive Dacogen

464
00:27:51.744 --> 00:27:54.684
or Hydrea, about 84, 86 per group.

465
00:27:56.144 --> 00:27:59.824
And their accrual time from start to finish was 18 months.

466
00:27:59.904 --> 00:28:01.584
Now, unfortunately, this was a negative study,

467
00:28:02.684 --> 00:28:06.604
but it shows clearly that with just a handful of centers, these studies

468
00:28:07.144 --> 00:28:07.904
can be done.

469
00:28:08.824 --> 00:28:12.534
This is another example just presented a few months ago at the American Society of

470
00:28:12.564 --> 00:28:16.484
Hematology meeting, that Dan Weissman and colleagues from the UK

471
00:28:16.944 --> 00:28:20.544
randomized 50 and 26 patients to receive

472
00:28:22.104 --> 00:28:25.784
727 or hydroxyurea respectively.

473
00:28:25.864 --> 00:28:29.644
And their accrual finished four months early, 18

474
00:28:29.664 --> 00:28:32.363
months total. So these can be done.

475
00:28:32.904 --> 00:28:36.864
These are rare diseases, but when you don't have a disease or a

476
00:28:36.884 --> 00:28:40.464
disease-modifying therapy, there's a tremendous

477
00:28:40.524 --> 00:28:41.824
opportunity to accrue quickly.

478
00:28:43.744 --> 00:28:47.004
So what about endpoints? And I think this is among the more important topics to

479
00:28:47.044 --> 00:28:50.404
discuss. And the short answer in CMML is we're trying.

480
00:28:51.204 --> 00:28:54.444
So there were response criteria that

481
00:28:54.484 --> 00:28:58.404
were established in 2015. They're being updated

482
00:28:58.484 --> 00:29:02.304
now by Mike Savona, Doug Trembley, Tony Hunter, and others.

483
00:29:03.944 --> 00:29:07.724
But the biggest challenge here is that it is among the most

484
00:29:07.804 --> 00:29:09.664
clinically heterogeneous diseases.

485
00:29:10.124 --> 00:29:14.104
So I hope we get a chance to talk about this in the panel, but the right endpoint

486
00:29:14.624 --> 00:29:18.204
in diseases that are this heterogeneous have to do with the

487
00:29:18.284 --> 00:29:22.214
specific drug itself and what we think that biology of where

488
00:29:22.214 --> 00:29:26.144
that drug is going to do which will dictate endpoints in

489
00:29:26.184 --> 00:29:30.014
future studies, and so that becomes quite challenging, and hopefully we can

490
00:29:30.044 --> 00:29:33.084
talk about some ideas on how to overcome that barrier.

491
00:29:35.364 --> 00:29:39.084
So I just want to summarize that we think that there are four barriers

492
00:29:39.624 --> 00:29:43.084
that slow clinical drug development in CMML and probably other rare cancers,

493
00:29:43.804 --> 00:29:47.254
but they're being addressed. And so I just wanted to put a plug for Blood Cancers

494
00:29:47.504 --> 00:29:50.944
United, who have put tremendous amount of resources in

495
00:29:51.344 --> 00:29:53.204
CMML research and advocacy

496
00:29:54.464 --> 00:29:58.424
to show that these drugs can be done, to show that the true incidence

497
00:29:58.464 --> 00:30:01.504
of CMML is comparable to a variety of other

498
00:30:02.484 --> 00:30:06.024
cancers in which drugs have been approved, and to show that there's an economic

499
00:30:06.064 --> 00:30:09.844
case. I think where it all starts

500
00:30:10.084 --> 00:30:13.444
is the preclinical studies to understand the convergent

501
00:30:13.524 --> 00:30:17.144
biology as well as a mutationally directed biology that can be

502
00:30:17.164 --> 00:30:18.464
therapeutically exploited.

503
00:30:20.004 --> 00:30:23.824
And then the feasibility of Phase III trials in the United

504
00:30:23.944 --> 00:30:25.724
States remains to be

505
00:30:27.564 --> 00:30:31.224
formally tested, but if they can do it in the UK and they can do it in France, I

506
00:30:31.244 --> 00:30:32.084
think we can do it here.

507
00:30:33.484 --> 00:30:36.804
And last, the endpoints, which I think is the most difficult one.

508
00:30:38.684 --> 00:30:41.624
New response criteria are being established, but I think it'll

509
00:30:41.704 --> 00:30:45.272
takea very detailed case-by-case analysis

510
00:30:45.312 --> 00:30:49.292
between the sponsor, the investigator, and the FDA to

511
00:30:49.332 --> 00:30:53.132
determine the right endpoint for the right drug for the

512
00:30:53.172 --> 00:30:54.792
right set of patients with CMML.

513
00:30:56.512 --> 00:31:00.202
So my prediction is, and I always keep saying this, let's just get one.

514
00:31:00.292 --> 00:31:04.232
Once we get that first approval, I think the roadmap will be

515
00:31:04.332 --> 00:31:08.072
set. I think there will be some certainty into what is the

516
00:31:08.112 --> 00:31:11.872
pathway forward for both investigators and industry.

517
00:31:12.872 --> 00:31:15.132
And I really do think many will follow after that.

518
00:31:15.482 --> 00:31:17.732
And our hope is that these barriers will be

519
00:31:19.292 --> 00:31:22.592
pushed away so we can have new therapies in CMML. And thank you for your attention.

520
00:31:29.672 --> 00:31:30.192
Nice job.

521
00:31:33.132 --> 00:31:33.652
Thank you, Rick.

522
00:31:34.852 --> 00:31:38.502
Next, Rachel Grisham will present a talk on development

523
00:31:38.532 --> 00:31:41.932
of the first FDA-approved treatment for women with low-grade

524
00:31:41.952 --> 00:31:43.342
serous ovarian cancer.

525
00:31:45.612 --> 00:31:49.492
Thanks, Dan. I'm so happy to be here today, and before we go to our panel

526
00:31:49.532 --> 00:31:53.232
discussion, I hope we're going to end on a high point here, talking

527
00:31:53.272 --> 00:31:57.132
about what I think is truly a huge success story, and to tell you

528
00:31:57.212 --> 00:32:00.752
about the development of this first treatment that was FDA approved for women with

529
00:32:00.792 --> 00:32:04.512
low-grade serous ovarian cancer, in part because of many of the

530
00:32:04.532 --> 00:32:07.492
programs that Martha described to us at the beginning of this session.

531
00:32:08.492 --> 00:32:11.732
These are my disclosures. My name is Rachel Grisham, and I'm a

532
00:32:11.772 --> 00:32:15.712
Gynecologic Medical Oncologist at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center

533
00:32:15.772 --> 00:32:16.332
in New York.

534
00:32:17.932 --> 00:32:21.532
So when I first started as a medical oncologist, we really thought about ovarian

535
00:32:21.652 --> 00:32:25.552
cancer as epithelial ovarian cancer, the common type of ovarian

536
00:32:25.592 --> 00:32:28.872
cancer arising from the outside of the ovary, and then some rare

537
00:32:28.912 --> 00:32:32.392
parenchymal tumors like sex cord stromal tumors and germ cell

538
00:32:32.432 --> 00:32:32.992
tumors.

539
00:32:33.812 --> 00:32:37.692
But over the course of the past 15 years, in large part

540
00:32:37.732 --> 00:32:41.082
due to the routine use of comprehensive sequencing, first in the

541
00:32:41.152 --> 00:32:44.912
laboratory and now in routine clinical practice, we've come to

542
00:32:44.992 --> 00:32:48.532
realize that epithelial ovarian cancer is really a group

543
00:32:48.972 --> 00:32:52.372
of histologically and molecularly distinct diseases

544
00:32:52.892 --> 00:32:55.292
which warrant individualized treatment.

545
00:32:55.962 --> 00:32:59.872
The most common of these is high-grade serous ovarian cancer.

546
00:32:59.932 --> 00:33:03.372
This accounts for about 70% of cases of epithelial ovarian

547
00:33:03.492 --> 00:33:07.312
cancer. We now realize that this type of cancer actually usually

548
00:33:07.372 --> 00:33:10.252
originates in the fallopian tube and spreads to the

549
00:33:10.332 --> 00:33:14.321
ovary. These are rapidly dividing cells, and about a quarter of

550
00:33:14.352 --> 00:33:18.052
our patients with high-grade serous ovarian cancer will have a germline or somatic

551
00:33:18.092 --> 00:33:21.622
BRCA mutation, and about 50% of these patients will have

552
00:33:21.622 --> 00:33:23.722
homologous recombination deficiency.

553
00:33:24.572 --> 00:33:28.212
And then we have rarer subtypes of epithelial ovarian cancer,

554
00:33:28.872 --> 00:33:32.792
such as endometrioid and clear cell ovarian cancer, that we now

555
00:33:32.832 --> 00:33:36.792
realize actually most frequently develop from endometriosis

556
00:33:37.192 --> 00:33:40.892
and therefore have a molecular profile more similar to that of endometrial

557
00:33:40.952 --> 00:33:44.772
cancer, with PI3 kinase mutations, PTEN loss,

558
00:33:44.912 --> 00:33:48.642
ARID1A mutations, and sometimes these tumors are MSI high.

559
00:33:49.632 --> 00:33:53.392
And now we realize that mucinous ovarian cancer is actually an

560
00:33:53.432 --> 00:33:57.412
occult GI primary in 50% of cases. So actually

561
00:33:57.452 --> 00:34:01.112
an appendiceal, small intestine, or pancreatic cancer that has

562
00:34:01.152 --> 00:34:04.942
metastasized to the ovary and is really best treated with

563
00:34:05.012 --> 00:34:08.462
GI regimens. But what we're going to talk about today is

564
00:34:08.612 --> 00:34:11.392
low-grade serous ovarian cancer.

565
00:34:11.422 --> 00:34:15.172
This accounts for about 8 to 10% of epithelial ovarian cancer

566
00:34:15.232 --> 00:34:19.092
cases. Unfortunately, the majority of women with this disease

567
00:34:19.112 --> 00:34:23.092
present with advanced metastatic stage III or IV disease when they're

568
00:34:23.132 --> 00:34:26.632
first diagnosed. And this cancer disproportionately

569
00:34:26.692 --> 00:34:30.632
affects young women. More than 20% of our patients with low-grade

570
00:34:30.652 --> 00:34:33.832
serous ovarian cancer are diagnosed before the age of 40.

571
00:34:34.352 --> 00:34:37.732
Many of my patients are diagnosed in their teens or early 20s.

572
00:34:38.592 --> 00:34:42.553
These are slower growing tumors, but because of that, they're less sensitive to

573
00:34:42.592 --> 00:34:45.872
traditional chemotherapy. Response rates to

574
00:34:45.892 --> 00:34:49.712
chemotherapy in the first-line setting are less than 25%

575
00:34:50.203 --> 00:34:54.092
and rapidly fall down to the single digits in the recurrent setting.

576
00:34:55.101 --> 00:34:58.321
These tumors do not have BRCA mutations or homologous

577
00:34:58.372 --> 00:35:02.071
recombination deficiency, but we do now understand that the

578
00:35:02.112 --> 00:35:05.932
majority of these tumors are driven by alterations in the MAP

579
00:35:05.972 --> 00:35:09.892
kinase pathway, most commonly KRAS mutations, which are found

580
00:35:09.932 --> 00:35:12.392
in about a third of patients with this disease.

581
00:35:13.412 --> 00:35:17.132
Because of this, there was early interest in the use of MEK inhibitors to try to

582
00:35:17.172 --> 00:35:19.792
treat patients with low-grade serous ovarian cancer.

583
00:35:20.422 --> 00:35:24.292
And two prior large Phase III studies have successfully been

584
00:35:24.332 --> 00:35:27.952
performed in women with recurrent low-grade serous ovarian

585
00:35:28.012 --> 00:35:31.972
cancer. One of these was called GOG 281, and the other one was

586
00:35:32.012 --> 00:35:35.452
called the MILO study. Both of these looked at the use of

587
00:35:35.592 --> 00:35:39.492
single-agent MEK inhibitors versus physician's choice of therapy

588
00:35:39.552 --> 00:35:43.392
for women with recurrent low-grade serous ovarian cancer.

589
00:35:43.452 --> 00:35:47.072
These did show initial promising response with the use of single-agent MEK

590
00:35:47.112 --> 00:35:50.192
inhibitor, with a response rate of 16% for

591
00:35:53.812 --> 00:35:57.512
benimetinib and 26% for trametinib, but these were

592
00:35:57.552 --> 00:36:01.132
limited by toxicity. Ultimately, about a third of patients

593
00:36:01.252 --> 00:36:05.112
treated with continuous single-agent MEK inhibitor discontinued treatment due

594
00:36:05.152 --> 00:36:06.072
to toxicity.

595
00:36:07.372 --> 00:36:11.352
Ultimately, neither of these studies led to FDA approval of MEK inhibitors for

596
00:36:11.392 --> 00:36:13.632
low-grade serous ovarian cancer.

597
00:36:13.652 --> 00:36:17.392
But ultimately, actually, both of these agents were NCCN compendium

598
00:36:17.432 --> 00:36:21.372
listed for treatment of the disease due to lack of effective therapies.

599
00:36:22.222 --> 00:36:25.912
So we really wanted to build on this initial efficacy seen with

600
00:36:25.952 --> 00:36:29.312
single-agent MEK inhibitors and try to decrease toxicity

601
00:36:29.852 --> 00:36:33.722
by using combination therapy that would more effectively target that

602
00:36:33.852 --> 00:36:37.012
pathway, but intermittent dosing to decrease

603
00:36:37.092 --> 00:36:40.760
toxicity.Avutametinib is a first-in-class

604
00:36:40.860 --> 00:36:44.600
RAF/MEK clamp, and defactinib is an oral Fak

605
00:36:44.620 --> 00:36:48.240
inhibitor. The combination of avutametinib and

606
00:36:48.260 --> 00:36:52.060
defactinib with intermittent dosing in the phase one

607
00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:55.700
FRAME study showed very promising response rates

608
00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:59.540
across multiple solid tumors, but in particular

609
00:36:59.640 --> 00:37:03.480
for women with low-grade serous ovarian cancer, where the response

610
00:37:03.580 --> 00:37:07.020
rate was greater than 40% and with durable

611
00:37:07.180 --> 00:37:10.940
responses that lasted a median of 27 months.

612
00:37:11.780 --> 00:37:15.660
Based on these promising results, this led to FDA breakthrough therapy

613
00:37:15.740 --> 00:37:18.980
designation for avutametinib in combination with

614
00:37:19.080 --> 00:37:22.440
defactinib. So when the makers of avutametinib and

615
00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:26.390
defactinib first came to me and were interested in partnering on the

616
00:37:26.460 --> 00:37:30.430
development of a registration-directed phase two study, I

617
00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:33.640
was very excited to see this early efficacy data.

618
00:37:34.220 --> 00:37:37.960
But we knew that there would be challenges and hurdles in the clinical

619
00:37:38.020 --> 00:37:39.010
trial design.

620
00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:43.630
So these two studies that I mentioned before, the GOG 281 study,

621
00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:48.060
took more than four years to enroll 260 patients across

622
00:37:48.220 --> 00:37:52.060
84 hospitals. And the MILO study took about three

623
00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:55.980
years to enroll 300 patients across 102 different

624
00:37:56.060 --> 00:37:59.930
sites in 20 different countries. So a lot of those sites

625
00:37:59.980 --> 00:38:03.360
enrolled zero or one patient, and there was considerable use of

626
00:38:03.380 --> 00:38:06.140
resources in order to complete that study.

627
00:38:07.540 --> 00:38:11.379
So based on limited resources, we wanted to develop this phase two

628
00:38:11.420 --> 00:38:15.320
study in the most efficient way possible and answer multiple

629
00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:18.640
different questions at once. So this study is called the

630
00:38:18.740 --> 00:38:22.480
NGOD-OV60 GOG 3052 RAMP 201

631
00:38:22.560 --> 00:38:26.160
study, and we enrolled women with recurrent low-grade serous ovarian

632
00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:30.180
cancer who had measurable disease and had received at least one prior line of

633
00:38:30.220 --> 00:38:32.010
chemotherapy. Because

634
00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:36.440
standard of care therapies are not very effective for this disease, we allowed

635
00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:39.110
patients to have unlimited additional lines of therapy.

636
00:38:39.820 --> 00:38:43.760
And patients were stratified by KRAS mutation status because we felt it would

637
00:38:43.780 --> 00:38:47.720
be a potential biomarker for response to treatment and also because

638
00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:49.740
we knew it was a prognostic indicator.

639
00:38:50.180 --> 00:38:53.540
Patients with KRAS-mutant disease and low-grade serous ovarian cancer have an

640
00:38:53.580 --> 00:38:57.440
improved prognosis versus KRAS wild-type patients.

641
00:38:58.280 --> 00:39:01.620
And this study was really designed to answer three different questions.

642
00:39:02.240 --> 00:39:06.180
In parts A and B of the study, patients were initially randomized to

643
00:39:06.220 --> 00:39:10.000
treatment with combination avutametinib and defactinib versus

644
00:39:10.040 --> 00:39:12.939
avutametinib as a single agent at a higher dose.

645
00:39:13.360 --> 00:39:17.060
So this was really to look at the relative contribution of combination

646
00:39:17.100 --> 00:39:19.260
therapy versus single-agent therapy.

647
00:39:20.040 --> 00:39:23.660
It was found that the combination therapy had a higher response rate

648
00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.200
and similar side effects to the single agent avutametinib.

649
00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:31.600
Therefore, in the expansion regimen, part C, additional patients

650
00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:35.620
were accrued to the combination therapy so that we would have more than 100

651
00:39:35.660 --> 00:39:39.540
patients who had been treated with the combination dosing for

652
00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:40.940
efficacy analysis.

653
00:39:41.880 --> 00:39:45.520
And then in part D, the dose optimization cohort, we looked at a lower

654
00:39:45.620 --> 00:39:49.400
dose of avutametinib, since a higher dose had already been examined in

655
00:39:49.440 --> 00:39:53.060
parts A and B. It was found that a lower dose avutametinib in

656
00:39:53.120 --> 00:39:57.000
combination with defactinib was suboptimal in terms of efficacy when

657
00:39:57.040 --> 00:39:58.840
compared to the standard dosing.

658
00:40:00.360 --> 00:40:03.620
During the course of this study, it was very important

659
00:40:04.380 --> 00:40:08.220
to the makers of avutametinib and defactinib to try to receive orphan

660
00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:11.920
drug designation. Now, we knew this would be difficult because this had

661
00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:15.760
never been achieved for any drug trying to treat

662
00:40:15.860 --> 00:40:18.120
low-grade serous ovarian cancer in the past.

663
00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:21.440
And a huge part of ultimately achieving this orphan drug

664
00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:24.280
designation was our patient advocates.

665
00:40:24.610 --> 00:40:28.280
And so I have to credit Verastem for being incredibly involved with patient

666
00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:31.680
advocates from the really beginning of this drug development

667
00:40:31.780 --> 00:40:35.680
process. And we have Nicole Andrews here today, and so I don't want to speak to

668
00:40:35.720 --> 00:40:37.620
this because she can speak to it so much better than me.

669
00:40:37.700 --> 00:40:41.360
She did a wonderful job of mobilizing her community

670
00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:45.360
to present a five-hour webinar about why drug

671
00:40:45.420 --> 00:40:48.340
development for low-grade serous ovarian cancer was so important.

672
00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:52.920
And this really spoke to the FDA and other stakeholders and ultimately led to

673
00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:54.560
this orphan drug designation.

674
00:40:56.040 --> 00:40:59.960
So we completed the study, and it showed unprecedented results for patients

675
00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:03.400
with low-grade serous ovarian cancer, with an overall response rate of

676
00:41:03.540 --> 00:41:07.460
31% and a response rate of 44% in those patients who had

677
00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:11.420
a KRAS mutation. And what was really remarkable was the durability of

678
00:41:11.480 --> 00:41:15.440
these responses, with a median PFS of 22 months for those

679
00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:19.360
patients with a KRAS mutation and a median duration of response of

680
00:41:19.420 --> 00:41:22.220
more than 31 months for the group overall.

681
00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:27.200
So based on these results, Verastem submitted a new drug

682
00:41:27.320 --> 00:41:30.950
application to the FDA in December of 2024,

683
00:41:31.440 --> 00:41:35.400
requesting accelerated approval for avutametinib and defactinib

684
00:41:35.420 --> 00:41:39.000
for patients with KRAS-mutant recurrent low-grade serous ovarian

685
00:41:39.100 --> 00:41:42.820
cancer. This was granted priority review, and in less than

686
00:41:42.880 --> 00:41:46.160
six months, accelerated approval was granted to the

687
00:41:46.200 --> 00:41:49.810
combination of avutametinib and defactinib for women with recurrent

688
00:41:49.920 --> 00:41:52.760
KRAS-mutant low-grade serous ovarian cancer.

689
00:41:52.970 --> 00:41:55.620
So a huge achievement for our patients.

690
00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:59.400
At the time of this approval, the confirmatory phase three study called the RAMP

691
00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:03.410
301 study was about two-thirds accrued, because it was of course

692
00:42:03.460 --> 00:42:06.640
important that we had substantially accrued to that study at that time.

693
00:42:07.440 --> 00:42:11.380
Now, one of the considerations in this setting is, do you go for your confirmatory

694
00:42:11.460 --> 00:42:15.090
phase three study in the same setting or an earlier line?

695
00:42:15.860 --> 00:42:19.760
Because early line studies in ovarian cancer are very large and lengthy, we

696
00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:23.400
did go for the same setting and so accrued to a similar patient

697
00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:27.060
population, and again, stratified by KRAS mutation

698
00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:31.000
status, and then randomized patients to the combination of

699
00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:34.760
avutametinib and defactinib versus investigator's choice of

700
00:42:34.800 --> 00:42:35.330
therapy.

701
00:42:36.180 --> 00:42:39.740
Now, of note, the accelerated approval is specifically for the KRAS mutant

702
00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:43.720
patients because those patients have the highest response rate and the highest

703
00:42:43.760 --> 00:42:47.720
PFS, but these drugs do also show activity in the KRAS wild

704
00:42:47.780 --> 00:42:51.220
type population. But we know that that's a poorer prognosis group

705
00:42:51.300 --> 00:42:54.908
overall.So the Phase 3 design was designed with a

706
00:42:54.948 --> 00:42:58.868
hierarchical statistical analysis to look first at the KRAS mutant

707
00:42:58.908 --> 00:43:02.688
patients' PFS, and then to look at the overall population

708
00:43:02.728 --> 00:43:06.548
PFS, with the hope that this confirmatory Phase 3 study

709
00:43:06.588 --> 00:43:10.488
may potentially expand the approval to all patients with recurrent low-grade

710
00:43:10.508 --> 00:43:11.968
serous ovarian cancer.

711
00:43:14.428 --> 00:43:18.368
Now, one idea, of course, with drugs that look incredibly promising

712
00:43:18.388 --> 00:43:22.328
for treatment of disease, especially a rare disease like this, we always want to

713
00:43:22.388 --> 00:43:25.888
think about moving to the frontline setting as quickly as possible.

714
00:43:26.908 --> 00:43:30.708
Now, for this particular drug combination, we chose not to go straight into a

715
00:43:30.748 --> 00:43:33.928
large Phase 3 study looking at the frontline setting.

716
00:43:34.248 --> 00:43:38.188
But we did want to move forward with seeing if this would be an efficacious

717
00:43:39.368 --> 00:43:42.828
option to replace our standard of care for current first-line

718
00:43:42.908 --> 00:43:46.648
therapy. So we chose to start an investigator-initiated

719
00:43:46.748 --> 00:43:50.408
study at my institution, Sloan Kettering, that would look at those

720
00:43:50.448 --> 00:43:54.308
patients that have the poorest prognosis, patients with newly

721
00:43:54.368 --> 00:43:58.288
diagnosed low-grade serous ovarian cancer that's too extensive

722
00:43:58.368 --> 00:44:02.068
for primary debulking surgery. These patients typically, unfortunately, have

723
00:44:02.188 --> 00:44:06.028
very poor outcomes. And in this study, we allow these patients to be treated

724
00:44:06.068 --> 00:44:09.748
with avutametinib and defactinib in combination with letrozole in the

725
00:44:09.768 --> 00:44:13.758
